{"source_key":"sha256-65bfebc5f4847475a374c871dbedf3ab","record_index":17,"record_hash":"sha256:a7c3e24b84bcbb7478dfbbef4ba36827a138c1d06c7c4869ff230b636539ca45","timestamp":"2026-05-20T17:13:51.404Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: fb3992\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2841\nOutput:\n# Including Turns In Agentlog\n\nThis note explores an evolution of `but-agentlog`: add a durable concept of a\ncapture turn between the project-scoped session and the captured transcript\nrecords.\n\nThe motivation is the session-association problem. The older\n[Session Association Strategy](session-association-strategy.md) is right to be\ncautious about capture-time ownership, but it treats the captured session mostly\nas one coarse object. In practice, the hook flow already gives us a more useful\nunit: every stop hook invocation is effectively a capture after an agent turn.\n\nToday `but-agentlog` deduplicates transcript records into one project session:\n\n```text\nproject session -> transcript records\n```\n\nThat stores the conversation, but it loses which newly observed records belonged\nto which capture invocation. It also loses the repository state that was true at\nthat moment. A capture turn layer would preserve that missing context without\nforcing us to immediately claim that the session \"belongs\" to a branch, commit,\nchange, or pull request.\n\n## V1 Contract\n\nImplement v1 around persisted capture observations, derived indexes, and\nread-time association. Do not persist inferred ownership.\n\nPersisted hierarchy:\n\n```text\nproject\n  session\n    capture turns\n      transcript records\n```\n\nStorage shape:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:turns = list<TurnSummary JSON>\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:turn:<turn-key> = TurnDetail JSON\n```\n\nCore rules:\n\n- A capture turn is created only when capture accepts at least one new\n  transcript record.\n- `TurnDetail.records` is an ordered array and is authoritative for rendering\n  order within the capture turn.\n- Backfilled capture turns may contain many logical conversation/provider turns,\n  so records must carry provider/display grouping metadata when available.\n- `turn_key` is `sha256-<32 lowercase hex chars>`, computed from UTF-8 stored\n  `session_key`, `s\n[TRUNCATED]\n service that can show reviewers what\nhappened behind a branch or pull request:\n\n- prompts\n- assistant responses\n- tool calls\n- planning depth\n- discussed edge cases\n- follow-up questions\n\nFor this use case, capture turns are more valuable than whole-session links\nbecause a session may span unrelated work. A review view can start from a\nbranch, change, or PR, find related sessions, and then use capture turn evidence\nto highlight the likely relevant parts of those sessions. Commit-centric lookup\ncan come later by resolving through change or branch evidence; it does not need\nits own v1 index.\n\nThe important line remains: capture turns can provide evidence and suggestions\nwithout automatically asserting durable ownership.\n\n## Proposed Hierarchy\n\nThe broader data hierarchy becomes:\n\n```text\none session -> many capture turns -> many records\n```\n\nA session remains the durable project-scoped object. A capture turn represents\none capture invocation, usually one observed agent stop-hook run. Transcript\nrecords remain the normalized conversation/tool events that `but-agentlog`\nalready stores and deduplicates.\n\nThis is deliberately not:\n\n```text\nbranch -> session -> records\n```\n\nBranches, changes, commits, and pull requests should still reference sessions or\ncapture turns. They should not own transcript data.\n\nIn this document, \"turn\" means **capture turn** unless explicitly qualified. A\ncapture turn is the durable storage unit. UI/read paths may still render\n**conversation turns** or **provider turns** inside a capture turn, especially\nfor handoff and backfilled sessions.\n\n## What A Capture Turn Means\n\nA capture turn is the unit of \"what we observed this time.\"\n\nEvery time the capture flow runs:\n\n1. parse the transcript snapshot\n2. deduplicate against already stored record hashes\n3. append only new transcript records\n4. write a capture turn object describing this capture invocation\n5. record which transcript records belong to the capture turn\n6. record enough repository environment state to support later association\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T17:13:51.404Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}